When delivering an event using the Event.dispatchEventAsynchronous method, the listener list is currently passed as reference to the eventThread for dispatch. This can cause listeners to be missed if the listeners are being removed just after the call to dispatchEventAsynchronous.
Instead of just passing a reference of the listener list, a copy of it should be done.

Here is an example showing the problem:
public class Activator implements BundleActivator {

	class SomeEventListener {
		public void somethingOccured(Object o) {
			System.out.println("listener notified");
		}
	}

	/*
	 * (non-Javadoc)
	 * @see org.osgi.framework.BundleActivator#start(org.osgi.framework.BundleContext)
	 */
	public void start(BundleContext context) throws Exception {
		EventManager eventManager = new EventManager("Supernova Event Dispatcher Thread");
		EventListeners eventListeners = new EventListeners();

		SomeEventListener sel = new SomeEventListener();

		// Add a SomeEventListener to the listener list
		eventListeners.addListener(sel, null);

		// Asynchronously deliver a SomeEvent to registered SomeEventListeners
		// Create the listener queue for this event delivery
		ListenerQueue listenerQueue = new ListenerQueue(eventManager);
		// Add the listeners to the queue and associate them with the event dispatcher
		listenerQueue.queueListeners(eventListeners, new EventDispatcher() {
			public void dispatchEvent(Object eventListener, Object listenerObject, int eventAction, Object eventObject) {
				try {
					((SomeEventListener) eventListener).somethingOccured("far");
				} catch (Throwable t) {
					// properly log/handle any Throwable thrown by the listener
				}
			}
		});
		// Deliver the event to the listeners. 
		listenerQueue.dispatchEventAsynchronous(0, new String("foo"));

		// Remove the listener from the listener list
		eventListeners.removeListener(sel);

		// Close EventManager to clean when done to terminate async event dispatch thread
		eventManager.close();
	}

	/*
	 * (non-Javadoc)
	 * @see org.osgi.framework.BundleActivator#stop(org.osgi.framework.BundleContext)
	 */
	public void stop(BundleContext context) throws Exception {
	}

}

Also, even if you move the removeListener call just before the dispatchEventAsynchronous:

                // Remove the listener from the listener list
                eventListeners.removeListener(sel);

                // Deliver the event to the listeners. 
                listenerQueue.dispatchEventAsynchronous(0, new String("foo"));

the event is still delivered since the list of listeners to which the event will be dispatched is built by the queueListeners call.

The first time you may access your preference initializer is in internalGet which is the likely first method you will hit in your preference store.

The problem is that the preference initializer is the only place where we can be sure the preference store is hit only once.

The code says

if (searchContexts == null) {
			if (includeDefault) {
				return new IEclipsePreferences[] { getStorePreferences(),
						getDefaultPreferences() };
			}
			return new IEclipsePreferences[] { getStorePreferences() };
		}

getDefaultPreferences is what will enable the preference initializer.

